message.content:
Frank Sahwit's stated discovery time of 1:00 PM in Testimony 8 directly contradicts Cindy's Autopsy Report (Evidence 1), which places the time of death between 4:00 PM and 5:00 PM.  
{"evidence": 1, "testimony": 8}

Frank Sahwit claims he heard the time via a voice on the television (Testimony 1), but the Blackout Record (Evidence 4) shows there was no electricity from noon to 6 PM, making it impossible for the TV to be on.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 1}

Sahwit claims he “saw” the time on the table clock (Testimony 0), but the Blackout Record (Evidence 4) shows there was no electricity from noon to 6 PM, meaning any electric clock would have been dead and he could not have seen the time.

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 0}

Gumshoe claims he found a physical memo beside the victim’s body (Testimony 1), but Evidence 4 is not a paper note at all—it’s an audio recording saved on Maya’s cell phone. These two statements cannot both be true.

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 1}

April identifies the murder weapon as “The Thinker” statue-clock, but the actual physical evidence shows only the broken glass light stand (the shards), indicating the stand—not the clock—was used to inflict the fatal blow.  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 4}

The May Testimony (Evidence 9) states the victim ran to the right, but Redd White’s Testimony 8 claims the victim ran to the left.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 8}

Evidence 9 states the victim “ran to the right,” while Testimony 1 claims she “first ran to the left,” a direct contradiction.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 1}

Testimony 1 claims Mr. White saw the light stand lying on the floor, but Evidence 8’s floor plans show the stand was completely blocked from view from the office, making it impossible for him to have seen it.  
{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 1}

Testimony 3 claims White saw the glass light stand when entering the Fey & Co. office, but Evidence 8’s floor plan shows that the stand was completely blocked from view from the office.  
{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 1 claims Jack Hammer “and the rest” had been doing a run‑through since the morning, yet Evidence 7 is a bottle of sleeping pills bearing Hammer’s fingerprints found in the employee area—if he’d been taking sleeping pills he couldn’t have been actively rehearsing.  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

Oldbag insists that “no one else went there,” yet Evidence 18 clearly shows that Vasquez was driven to Studio One, directly contradicting her statement.  
{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 8 claims Cody didn’t have his camera with him at the crucial moment, directly contradicting Evidence 15 which states he “always carries” it.  
{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 8}

Cody claims in Testimony 3 that his camera’s lens wouldn’t open in time and he missed the shot entirely. Yet Evidence 5 is a timestamped photograph (Photo #2) showing Will Powers at the gate. This direct conflict indicates that Cody could take the picture despite his claim.

{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 3}

The contradiction lies between Dee Vasquez’s claim that she and Sal Manella ate t‑bone steaks on a table “in front of the trailer” (Testimony 5) and the forensic finding that the steak plate (evidence of their meal) was in the employee area, not by the trailer (Evidence 16).  
{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 5}

Vasquez claims that Will Powers was the only person absent when they found Jack Hammer’s body (Testimony 1), yet the timestamped photograph of Powers at the studio gate at 2:00 PM (Evidence 5) shows he was already on-site well before the body was discovered.  
{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 1}

Lotta claims she clearly saw Mr. Edgeworth on the boat, but the automatically taken Lake Photo (Evidence 4) shows two figures in dense fog where neither face is visible, directly contradicting her assertion.

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 0}

Testimony 3 claims Lotta set up her camera to photograph a meteor shower, but Evidence 2 clearly states the camera was configured to trigger on loud noises—directly contradicting her statement.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

The second lake photo was taken automatically at 11:50 PM on the 24th and shows no one there, yet Lotta claims testimony 3 that she was camping by the lake at that time.  
{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 3}

The second lake photo was taken automatically at 11:50 PM on the 24th and shows the lake entirely empty—yet Testimony 0 has Butz claiming he was out in a boat on the lake that night.  
{"evidence": 16, "testimony": 0}

The camera’s automatic lake photo (Evidence 4) was triggered by a loud noise at 12:15 AM on 12/25, meaning the shot happened then—contradicting Butz’s claim that he heard the gunshot “just when … ‘It’s almost Christmas!’” (Testimony 5), which would place it before midnight on 12/24.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 5}

Testimony 5 states that only a single gunshot was fired, whereas Evidence 10 shows the murder weapon was fired three times.  
{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 5}

Testimony 5 claims the victim definitely wrote “Maggie” in the sand using his right hand, but Evidence 6 shows he was wearing a custom-made glove on his right hand—making it impossible for him to leave fingernail scratches and write in the sand with that hand.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 5}

Testimony 5 claims that a “banana” fell with the officer, but the evidence (Evidence 6) clearly shows the object was a custom-made baseball glove shaped like a banana—not an actual banana.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 5}

Testimony 2 claims Wellington placed the call at 6:45 PM “immediately” after discovering the crime, but the autopsy report (Evidence 2) firmly establishes the victim’s time of death at 6:28 PM—making Wellington’s timeline impossible.  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 2}

Evidence 9 indicates that the victim’s fingerprints are on the gun, showing he handled the weapon in his own defense. That directly contradicts testimony 3’s claim that the victim “was not fighting back.”  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 3 states that the victim’s shot missed entirely, yet Evidence 11 shows a bullet hole in Maya’s sleeve—meaning the shot did hit her.  
{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 3}

Ini’s testimony that she saw her sister enter the room (Testimony 2) directly conflicts with the newspaper clipping (Evidence 6) which states that her sister Mimi Miney died in a car accident a year ago, making it impossible for her to have appeared.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 4 states that Ini “didn’t see anyone on the way to the Channeling Chamber,” but Evidence 14 explicitly places Pearl in the hallway fixing the urn just before the murder, meaning Ini must have passed by and seen her.  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 4}

The License Photo (evidence 18) clearly shows Ini Miney holds a valid driver’s license, directly contradicting her testimony (testimony 6) that she didn’t have a license and thus couldn’t drive.  
{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 6}

The newspaper clipping (Evidence 6) quotes Ini saying she “dropped off to sleep” and woke up amid the crash, clearly implying she was driving, whereas in her testimony 5 she insists she was merely the passenger that night. This direct conflict shows one or the other is lying.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 5}

Trilo insists he still had the engagement ring in his pocket at the time of the murder, but Evidence 10 shows that the ring is now in Phoenix’s possession, directly contradicting Trilo’s statement.

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 5}

Trilo Quist is a puppet and cannot move by himself, so his claim of waiting for Regina at the plaza directly contradicts Evidence 8.

{"evidence": 8, "testimony": 0}

Moe claims he saw a shadow at the scene that “could only have belonged to Max” (Testimony 0), but the crime photo (Evidence 2) clearly shows only the victim’s footprints leading to where he’s lying in the snow—with no sign of anyone else ever having been there. This direct conflict between Moe’s eyewitness account and the photographic evidence marks the contradiction.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 0}

Moe insists Max never removed his hat, yet the silk hat (Evidence 3) was found at the crime scene, implying it wasn’t being worn.  
{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 3}

Acro claims he “could have lifted something the size of that bust” (Testimony 0), but the evidence notes the bronze Max G. Bust “looks rather heavy” (Evidence 15), directly contradicting his assertion.  
{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 0}

Gumshoe’s claim that “the defendant bought the knife for the crime” is directly contradicted by the knife itself, which is engraved with “Gatewater,” indicating it was hotel property rather than a personal purchase.  
{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 5}

Oldbag claims she saw Engarde sneaking out in his flashy racing jacket, but Lotta’s photograph clearly shows someone in full samurai garb standing outside the victim’s door, not a racing jacket.  
{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 5}

Oldbag claims she saw the Nickel Samurai himself commit the stabbing, but the murderer was actually disguised as a bellboy, wearing the Bellboy’s Uniform recovered from De Killer’s hideout.  
{"evidence": 30, "testimony": 1}

Testimony 5 claims that the vase fell directly onto the guitar case, but the crime scene photo (evidence 9) clearly shows the vase shattered on the floor next to the case, not on top of it.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 5}

Andrews insists she opened the guitar case after knocking over the vase, yet Evidence 7 shows the case bears only Corrida’s fingerprints, proving she never touched it.  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

Testimony 2 claims there’s no way to prove Matt Engarde’s motive for murdering Juan Corrida, yet Evidence 27—the Celeste’s Suicide Note found in the wooden figurine—explicitly details Engarde’s misdeeds, providing concrete proof of his motive.  
{"evidence": 27, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 2 claims Corrida was “slumped over and tired‐looking in the corner,” implying he appeared alive and in a corner. Evidence 9’s crime scene photo, however, clearly shows him sitting on a chair by the dresser with a knife sticking out of his chest—dead and not in a corner.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 1 claims that Powers saw a bellboy emerge from Juan Corrida’s room, but Evidence 17’s hallway photo clearly shows a person in samurai garb—no bellboy—standing outside the door at the time.  
{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 15 shows the knife bears Engarde’s fingerprints, directly contradicting Testimony 5 where de Killer claims Andrews created and planted the knife.  
{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 5}

Testimony 4 states that de Killer thought his client was a man, but Evidence 11 refers to the client as “Ms. A.A.,” clearly indicating she is female.

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 4}

The photograph of the victim’s plain shirt directly contradicts Phoenix’s claim that Doug always wore a huge Union Jack on his back.

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 4}

The crime scene photograph clearly shows the umbrella lying at a distance from the victim, directly contradicting Phoenix’s claim that the victim fell on top of his umbrella.  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 3}

Evidence 6 states there was a loud sound when the victim fell on his umbrella, but Testimony 5 claims the witness “didn’t hear anything unusual.”  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 5}

Dahlia claims the very first impact was into the electrical pole and that the cable snapped at that moment (Testimony 1), but Phoenix swears the victim actually fell on top of his umbrella with a loud thud (Evidence 6)—those two accounts can’t both be true.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 1}

Phoenix’s claim that Doug died from falling onto his umbrella directly contradicts the autopsy report stating the cause of death was electrocution.

{"evidence": 1, "testimony": 6}

Testimony 1 claims DeMasque sends his calling card out of pure confidence before every heist, but Evidence 20 states that from his second heist onward he was operating under blackmail—hardly something done with freedom and confidence.  
{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 6 states that Mask☆DeMasque knocked Atmey out with a blow to the back of his head, whereas Testimony 2 has Atmey claiming he was struck “just as I began to turn,” implying a frontal or side attack rather than one from behind.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

The testimony says Atmey was struck on the “third eye” (forehead), but the Shichishito evidence clearly states the thief knocked him out with a blow to the back of the head, directly contradicting his claim.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 5}

Testimony 2 claims Ron had no alibi for the night of the urn’s theft, yet Evidence 12 shows his key card was used at 1 AM that same night—giving him exactly that alibi.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 2}

Atmey claims in Testimony 1 that the urn was boxed up and sent to the warehouse, but Evidence 4 clearly states the Sacred Urn was still in his office, contradicting his statement.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 1}

Testimony 4 claims that the defendant “truly believes he is Mask DeMasque,” but Evidence 20 is Ron DeLite’s own testimony stating that he committed the heists only under blackmail, showing he did not believe himself to actually be Mask DeMasque.  
{"evidence":20, "testimony":4}

Testimony 2 claims the victim had no identification, yet Evidence 17 shows a prescription bag—complete with patient information—on the victim’s table.  
{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 2}

The crime scene photograph (Evidence 12) clearly shows that no one was seated across from the victim, yet Kudo’s Testimony 4 asserts that the “serving girl” was sitting in the defendant’s chair opposite the victim— a direct contradiction.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 2 claims that the victim knocked over a vase, yet Evidence 12’s crime scene photo clearly shows intact vases on both tables.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 2}

Jean Armstrong claims there was a mirror dividing the restaurant into two halves (Testimony 0), but the crime scene photograph (Evidence 12) clearly shows the two tables separated by a folding screen, not a mirror.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 0}

Testimony 3 claims there were no other customers present, yet Evidence 18 is Victor’s own testimony that he was sitting at a table and broke a vase when the incident occurred, proving at least one other customer was there.  
{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 1 claims Tigre spent all of December tied up in his office, yet Evidence 6 shows his fingerprints on a bottle in Tres Bien’s kitchen—he couldn’t have been in the office the whole time.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 6 shows Furio Tigre’s fingerprints on Glen’s ear medicine found in the kitchen of Tres Bien, directly contradicting Testimony 4 in which Tigre claims he’s never been to Tres Bien.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 4}

The floor plans show that the entrance doesn’t give a view of the victim’s table, so Tigre couldn’t have “seen one ugly scene” immediately upon opening the door.  
{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 1}

Testimony 2 asserts that Glen “had no way to pay up,” yet Evidence 14 reveals he possessed a half‐million‐dollar winning lottery ticket, directly contradicting that claim.  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 2}

Gumshoe claims there’s nothing unusual in the trunk photo (Testimony 4), yet the Crime Photo (Evidence 4) clearly shows the trunk opener has been tampered with—something he should have noticed but explicitly denies.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 3 claims the victim was stabbed from behind, but the witness’s photo (Evidence 6) clearly shows the assailant facing the victim from the front when the incident occurred, making these accounts incompatible.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 3}

Melissa’s own witness photo (Evidence 6) shows the two figures standing face‐to‐face with no sign of a scuffle, directly contradicting her claim that “they just started fighting!” (Testimony 2).

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

Melissa couldn’t have witnessed him carrying the body to the car, since the map (Evidence 2) shows her vantage point on the south side was blocked from the parking lot by huge rocks, directly contradicting her claim in Testimony 1.  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 1}

Melissa claims in Testimony 0 that she was out of the country until the year before last, yet Evidence 7 explicitly states that she took the witness’s photo at the time of the incident five years ago, making it impossible for her to have been absent from the country then.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 0}

The witness photograph (Evidence 6) clearly shows Fawles facing the victim directly, which contradicts Dahlia’s claim that he pushed her off from behind (Testimony 3).

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 2 states that Fawles “never put no body in that car,” but Evidence 4 (Crime Photo) clearly shows the victim’s body curled up in the trunk of his car, directly contradicting his statement.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 3 claims Iris came to the Inner Temple, but Evidence 12 (Iris’s own testimony) states she was in her room after ringing the lights‐out bell and never left.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 3}

The testimony that Iris didn’t have her hood on directly contradicts the evidence stating Iris wears her hood at all times.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 2 claims the witness saw the hidden blade being drawn from the hilt, yet Evidence 9 clearly states that the murder weapon’s sword was concealed inside Elise’s staff and known only to Detective Gumshoe and the narrator—no one else could have observed it.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 2}

The tracks photo (Evidence 14) clearly shows just a single set of prints leading to Dusky Bridge, whereas Bikini’s testimony (Testimony 2) claims she saw tracks “that indicated the snowmobile had been used,” which would leave two continuous tracks rather than one. 
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 2}

Evidence 14’s tracks photo shows only one set of footprints leading to Dusky Bridge, yet Testimony 5 claims that Butz arrived first and Phoenix showed up less than a minute later—two people would leave two sets of tracks, not one.  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 5}

Iris’s hood was given to Phoenix before lights out, so Iris couldn’t have been wearing it—and thus Butz’s claim that he saw her white hood fluttering is false.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 3 claims that Elise threw away her staff and used a dagger to kill the victim, but Evidence 9 establishes that the victim’s staff—with its hidden sword—was the actual murder weapon.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 3}

Iris’s own testimony (Evidence 12) says she was in her room from 10 PM on, yet in Testimony 0 she claims to have witnessed Maya being struck and stumbling.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 0}

The autopsy report (Evidence 11) states that Elise’s body fell only about 10 feet after being stabbed, yet Iris’s testimony #3 claims she dragged the body all the way across Dusky Bridge—a distance far exceeding 10 feet. 

{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 3}

The unlit stone lantern (Evidence 20) makes Maya’s claim of seeing by its light (Testimony 4) impossible. 

{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 4}

The torches Maya claims were lit (Testimony 3) directly contradicts the stone lantern being unlit that night (Evidence 20), since the temple wouldn’t have provided any extra lighting if no lanterns were burning.  
{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 3}

The Tracks Photo (Evidence 14) clearly shows footprints leading straight across Dusky Bridge that very night—meaning passage was possible—directly contradicting Maya’s claim that Pearl “was also stuck on the Inner Temple side that night.”  
{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 0}
{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 5}

Olga claims the victim was strangled to death (Testimony 4), but the autopsy clearly records death by a single blow to the forehead (Evidence 1).

{"evidence": 1, "testimony": 4}

Olga claims that “for [the] last hand, [the] defendant play[ed] with all chips on table and lose[d],” which would leave him with zero chips afterward. Yet the chip photo (Evidence 6) clearly shows the defendant still possessing several chips at the time of the murder.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 3 claims Mr. Smith held three aces, but Evidence 6’s chip photo shows he had only two aces.

{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 3}

Olga insists in Testimony 5 that she never let Wright out of her sight until the police arrived, yet Evidence 4 shows Wright left the basement and went to the first floor upstairs to make the call.  
{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 5}

Testimony 3 claims I removed a card from the game and hid it in the bottle, which would leave one of the hands incomplete—but Evidence 9 clearly shows the victim’s hand left at the scene is a full five-card hand (a full house), meaning no card was missing.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 3}

The autopsy report specifies the bullet entered the right temple, contradicting the eyewitness’s claim that it struck square in the forehead.  
{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 2 describes the victim dying from a gunshot, but Evidence 12 explicitly states the victim died pulling the noodle stand, ruling out a fatal gunshot.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 4 claims the stand’s sign read “NOODLE,” but Evidence 12 clearly shows the sign read “ELDOON,” directly contradicting the witness’s statement.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 4}

Alita claims she hadn’t been back to the clinic since quitting in January (Testimony 0), yet the Wocky’s Chart (Evidence 18) is signed by nurse Alita Tiala, proving she was still working there and contradicting her testimony.

{"evidence": 18, "testimony": 0}

Brushel’s claim that Misham collapsed “the next moment” after one sip conflicts directly with the Post‑Mortem finding that the atroquinine on the mug was slow‑acting.  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 6}

Brushel claims the envelope was yellow and left at the crime scene, but the only envelope recovered was red and found in the victim’s desk drawer.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 4 claims the pistol “definitely belonged to the old man,” but Evidence 20 identifies it as the stage magician’s prop (the Stage Pistol), not the victim’s personal firearm.  
{"evidence": 20, "testimony": 4}

Lamiroir claims she “saw nothing” (Testimony 0), yet the scene diagram (Evidence 10) clearly shows two bullet holes in the wall that would have been visible upon entering the room.

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 0}

Ema claims “no one in this country had a motive to kill the victim,” yet the newspaper article (Evidence 19) makes clear a strong motive existed—namely the remedy for the Chief Justice’s son’s incuritis.  
{"evidence": 19, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 3 claims Tonate saw the bomb’s timer counting down. However, Evidence 5 states that the switch which starts the bomb’s countdown was stolen and never used—so the timer could not have been activated.  
{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 2 claims that Apollo was able to look near the witness stand “where there was no rubble,” yet Evidence 6’s courtroom diagram clearly shows rubble blocking access to that very area.  
{"evidence": 6, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 1 claims that there was no bloody writing when Tonate first arrived on scene, but Evidence 7 (Apollo’s Assault Photo) clearly shows the bloody writing “L10015” present on the floor at that time.  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

Testimony 1 claims the writing read “L10015R,” but the Bloody Writing Analysis (Evidence 9) confirms it was written as “L10015,” making the witness’s statement directly contradictory.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 1}

A clear contradiction arises between the Fox and Demon Statue evidence, which notes that no fingerprints could be lifted from the murder weapon, and the testimony claiming the defendant’s fingerprints were found on that same weapon.

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

Evidence 12 is Jinxie’s eyewitness account of an actual demon near the crime scene, which directly contradicts Testimony 2’s claim that the monster was entirely fabricated by Mayor Tenma.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 2}

Jinxie’s eyewitness account (Evidence 12) states that she saw the demon run toward the foyer near the crime scene. Filch’s sworn testimony (Testimony 3) claims he “didn't see nothing outta the ordinary” while on guard there. These two statements directly contradict each other.

{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 3}

Filch claims there was no sign of Tenma Taro in the foyer (Testimony 4), but Jinxie’s eyewitness account (Evidence 12) explicitly states she saw the demon flee toward the foyer, directly contradicting his statement.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 4}

Filch claims the murderer was carrying a big staff (Testimony 2), but the autopsy report (Evidence 14) clearly states the victim was stabbed with a spear, not bludgeoned or struck with a staff.  

{"evidence": 14, "testimony": 2}

L'Belle’s claim that the mayor “stood up and opened the Forbidden Chamber” immediately after regaining consciousness directly clashes with Evidence 17, which states he had swallowed the only key. This makes it impossible for him to unlock the door at that moment.

{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 2}

The statue described in Evidence 7 depicts Tenma Taro and the Nine-Tailed Fox locked in battle, not dancing or celebrating a merger as L’Belle claims in Testimony 6.  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 6}

The white hair found inside the discarded Amazing Nine-Tails mask (Evidence 10) directly implies the hero is Mayor Tenma himself, conflicting with L’Belle’s assertion that “The Amazing Nine-Tails’s TRUE identity is NOT Mayor Tenma” (Testimony 0).

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 0}

Scuttlebutt claims the photo shows a plain blue costume (Testimony 4), but the actual glowing costume photo (Evidence 10) clearly shows fluorescent paint and star patterns, not a plain blue outfit.

{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 4}

Constance Courte’s planner clearly notes an “Important” meeting with Hugh on October 23rd (Evidence 2), yet Hugh O’Conner testifies that he “didn’t talk to anyone until the final bell” (Testimony 5)—making his statement impossible.  
{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 5}

Testimony 0 claims the entire campus was empty except for the lecture hall, but Evidence 11 shows people actively preparing in the art room, proving the campus was not empty at that time.  
{"evidence": 11, "testimony": 0}

Testimony 1 claims that Professor Means pre‑recorded his own speech in the audio room during the mock trial, yet Evidence 9 shows the only tape from that session is a fake recording of the line “You’re a goner!” lifted straight from Junie’s mock trial script—hardly a lawyer’s prerecorded address.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 1}

The security camera video (Evidence 7) shows Starbuck and Clay fleeing from a corridor into the boarding lounge, with no indication that they ever exited a rocket. This directly contradicts Starbuck’s claim that he “supported Clay over my shoulder and got us out of the rocket” (Testimony 0).

{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 0}

Testimony 2 claims that Starbuck was carrying the “Hope” capsule in his arms after the incident. However, Evidence 13 states that the capsule was found in the victim’s possession, meaning it never left the victim’s hands. These two statements cannot both be true.  
{"evidence": 13, "testimony": 2}

The only bullet hole found in the boarding lounge was made by a single .38‑caliber shot (Evidence 10), yet Cosmos claims Detective Arme fired two warning shots there (Testimony 4).  
{"evidence": 10, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 2 claims the suspect fired at Cosmos and Detective Arme while they were still in the Control Room. Yet Evidence 15 shows the only .38‐caliber bullet (Arme’s gun) was found by the victim’s oxygen tank—at the boarding lounge—indicating the shot was fired there, not in the Control Room.  
{"evidence": 15, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 3 places Metis’s body “near the round window on the workbench side,” yet Evidence 9’s photos show her lying on the operating table, opposite the workbench.  
{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 4 claims the lighter bears prints from the thumb, index, and middle fingers of a right hand, but Evidence 17 (Aura’s statement) specifies the perp held the lighter in their left hand—these directly conflict.

{"evidence": 17, "testimony": 4}

Evidence 12 (Moon Rock Earring) shows the “moon rock” in question is actually an earring gifted to Athena, not a raw meteorite tied to the phantom—contradicting Fulbright’s Testimony 0 that he feared the moon rock because it reminded him of the phantom.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 0}

DePlume’s claim that the whale “bit the victim to death with its huge mouth and deadly teeth” directly conflicts with the autopsy report showing instant death from blunt force trauma without any mention of bite wounds.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 2 claims Rimes saw “a bunch of coins scattered around” in the pool room, but Evidence 9 specifies that only a single coin was found by the side of the orca pool, directly contradicting his observation.

{"evidence": 9, "testimony": 2}

The orca couldn’t have killed him by bashing him in midair—according to Evidence 12, the fatal head trauma was from a fall, and the blow was suffered after death, directly contradicting Testimony 3.  
{"evidence": 12, "testimony": 3}

Evidence 5 states that all hallway shutters were shut during the Dance of Devotion, which would have blocked any view through those windows. Testimony 3 claims Andistan'dhin saw Ahlbi “through the window,” directly contradicting the evidence that the shutters were closed.  
{"evidence": 5, "testimony": 3}

The testimony claiming the box was forced open without a key (Testimony 3) directly contradicts the Magatama Key being the only way to open the treasure box (Evidence 7).  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 3}

Testimony 5 asserts that the defendant’s fingerprints were on the tape, but Evidence 3’s fingerprinting results explicitly state that there is no fingerprint evidence for Trucy Wright.  
{"evidence": 3, "testimony": 5}

Betty claims she helped “make sure we were prepared” for the dangerous fire trick (Testimony 2), but the Fire Bucket (Evidence 4) was found empty and covered in dust—clearly not ready for any emergency.

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 2}

Testimony 4 claims Ihmus saw the stabbing of the high priest, but Evidence 4 states the ritual curtain completely isolated the Inner Sanctum from outside view, making such an observation impossible.

{"evidence": 4, "testimony": 4}

Testimony 1 claims it was a “still night” with no wind, yet Evidence 7 shows the lantern’s wind guard was broken—indicating strong gusts that night.  
{"evidence": 7, "testimony": 1}

The May 9th Newspaper (Evidence 2) clearly states the ice around the Inner Sanctum had melted by the morning of the rite, making access possible, which directly contradicts Ihmus’s claim that it would have been impossible to get there (Testimony 2).

{"evidence": 2, "testimony": 2}
